%FEATURE_STRUCTURES.sofaString: Low energy magnetic domain wall logic - The aim of this project was to develop a magnetic logic device. This performs a similar function as a conventional transistor (or several transistors) made from silicon. However, the magnetic device has several potential advantages, including low power consumption, non-volatility which is the ability to ?remember? its state even after the power is switched off, and a small size. One magnetic logic device can replace several transistors to form a logic gate. In the project the device was designed, modeled using micromagnetic and electrical simulation programs, fabrication schemes were developed, and a prototype was built; combinations of devices to carry out complex logic operations were also modeled. The overall arrangement of the device is shown in Fig. 1. A narrow magnetic wire contains one domain wall. The domain wall is moved back and forth on the wire by an electric current pulse which forms the input of the device. When it is on the left the device state is ?1? and on the right the device state is ?0?. The device is switched to ?0? if the current, which is the sum of two input currents, is large enough. Otherwise the state is ?1?. The device therefore performs a NAND function. Modeling showed the feasibility of this approach and allowed calculations of ho the device would perform as its dimensions scaled down, in terms of speed and power consumption. More complex circuits such as a full adder were simulated. Device fabrication involved lithographic steps similar to those used in making silicon electronics. Methods were deviced to etch the magnetic films to produce smooth edges, shown in Figure 2, and domain wall behavior in the thin patterned wires was studied including measurements of domain wall pinning and simulations of the domain wall speed and pinning behavior. The readout element, a magnetic tunnel junction, was patterned using an ion beam etching process. Finally, a prototype device was made and tested. Figure 3 shows the device and its performance as a NAND gate. Combinations of devies are currently being tested to see if more complex logic functions can be carried out. Broader impacts of the work included training of graduate and undergraduate students in interdisciplinary research that spans between physics, materials science and electrical engineering. The findings of the project were incorporated into the PIs? teaching, including classes on magnetic materials and devices, and nanoelectronics. A class entitled Electrical, Optical and Magnetic Materials and Devices was prepared for free worldwide access though the edX platform and will be available to the public in Spring 2015. The PIs participated in summer outreach prgrans such as one for New England teachers introducing them to progress in magnetism and data storage.
